title: Grateful Dead Live at Carter-Finley Stadium on 1990-07-10
lineage: Cassette Master (Nakamichi DR-1) -> Sound Devices 744T (24bit/96k) -> Samplitude Professional v11.03 -> FLAC/16
description:
Set 1

Jack Straw*, Loser, We Can Run But We Can't Hide, Me & My Uncle-> Big River, Friend Of The Devil*, When I Paint My Masterpiece*, Bird Song*, Promised Land**

Set 2

Iko Iko*, Playin' In The Band*-> Uncle John's Band*-> Playin' In The Band Jam-> Drums-> Jam-> The Other One-> Stella Blue, Not Fade Away, E: Brokedown Palace

* with Bruce Hornsby on accordion. ** Done in 2 parts, power goes out; Bruce Hornsby & the Range opened

reviews.review_text:
Theres a power shortage in the  Promised Land This is another gift from Charlie Miller.  The sound is perfect.  The Jack Straw is a solid way to open the show.  It takes the band a little bit to warm up.  During Promised Land the power goes out and it takes the crew a few minutes to fix it and then they boys jump right back into the tune right where they left off.  I have never heard anything like this.  Iko second set opener is solid.  Good show overall.

BAMMER

Band Beyond Description Lightning hit the stage or very near it during Promised.  They continued to play briefly with nothing coming out.  They shrugged and walked off.  In about 3 minutes they came back and picked up note for note where they stopped like pressing 'play' from a 'stop'.  It was truly like nothing I have ever seen in well over 200 shows.  It was in the mid 100s that day, and the storm was welcome.  

This show's second set totally smokes.  The accordion, which I usually detested, does not detract all that much.  The Playin' sandwich makes this worth adding to your rotation.  The percolator was plugged in, and if you want a taste of the infinite you will get it here in set II.

Maybe only a 4* show, with it not being a spacey set I, but the transcendent effort in Promised rates the extra star.
summer tour 1990 well played show!not talked about much because of some of the other shows on this tour.no bad versions of any song!

UJB - Hall of Fame Caliber Just my 2 cents, but the UJB is, in my humble opinion, one of the best they've done.  Besides Jerry getting all the words right ( a rarity!), the jams are absolutely beautiful.  There are a number of stellar versions of course, but 1989-90 produced some of the finest versions out there.

The Sliding Incident Hi. Does anyone remember what song was playing when everyone starting sliding down the mud end zone? 

Great night. ONLY night I'll ever say that the cops were a horrible presence. There were NC State Troopers on horseback. The guy in the car next to me got busted...with opium...in North Carolina. Sucked to be him.

Overall, great night. Drove from Chicago all night, drove all night back, no sleep, one annoying passenger.

Taking of the hill Oh boy what a show the heads took the hill sone after the second set started little by little then alot by alot i was in the later..sone one made off my shoes I took off to dance..the heat,the power outage,the taking of the hill and that ripping second set. All make for a great memorie on a fun tour..OH AND I GOT MIRICALED !!

Sliding incident ALAN OSTERMAN-

YES! !!! it happened during MASTERPIECE! ***
 
I was already down on floor,  but in the back,  not far from porta-pottys, and we were watching as the people at the top were pushing in the fence -  I'd say most of us were cheering them on. .. when they came all came rushing /sliding down,  all the security guards were like headless chickens! 
They couldn't really catch anyone! 
(Maybe a handful)
Everyone was wet and slippery!!

-the one and only time they ever played at ralleigh as we were (not-so-kindly) asked to never return! !

...The energy from the hill incident still high, the power went out during  PROMISED LAND*  - just for a minute  - and when it came back,  the band picked up right where they left off! (It really was like pressing stop and start on a tape as DH225 stated)
*I'm grateful for this site - to be able to hear it all again... 
I remembered the power going out as happening the same time as the hill incident,  as my memories tend to mesh and blur with time.  So glad there's endless posterity with GD!!!!

***now,  listening to promised land,  I seem to be having a visual of watching everyone run (and slide) down hill with security chasing ... comical - like a benny hill skit !! ..
 So to be honest,  it could have happened during PL, or was still happening.  . (Oh memory... you are so elusive!)***

 One of my all-time favorite memories,  tho there are many. 
Thanks for reminding me of it!

 "To rock my soul"

Su90 Tour N4 (w/Bruce)  Thanks for the Shakedown Stream, Dave, this was a fun one!  Although, if I'm being honest, I'm more a fan of Hornsby's guest appearance(s) from the year prior at RFK. At points it feels like his accordion gets in the way; but 
there's no question that everyone was clearly having a blast. The fourth quarter takes the cake: Drumz->O1->Stella Blue->NFA with a beautiful Brokedown encore.
I was there! My one and only Dead show. It was so much fun. A beautiful show, and beautiful crowd. I still think about it, and I'm still friends with the people I went with!
